text: oh boy
hi everyone anthony fantano here
internet's busiest music nerd and time
for a review willis earl beale
acousmatic sorcery this is willis earl
beale's kind of official
label released debut album he's a
chicago singer-songwriter who's been
self-recording for for quite a while and
just on first listen
beale's musical foundation has a lot of
characteristics that reminds me of of
artists that i already love and respect
sometimes his tracks have kind of a
tom waits characteristic really kind of
clunky noisy percussion matched with
some really kind of bold
intense and growly vocals and sometimes
he has this
captain beefheart characteristic about
him where he'll be sort of doing some
really abstract out there spoken word
over some pretty noisy instrumentals
other times he has a bit of a daniel
johnston
angle to his songs with a very diy
lo-fi self-recorded aesthetic onto tape
so there is that kind of warbly sound
with the instruments
and occasionally his tracks do kind of
shoot for something that is a bit
confessional like embarrassingly
confessional and personal some of his
tracks pull influences from blues music
and gospel music whether it's from
lyrical ideas or chord progressions all
of these various influences really got
me psyched for this lp plus there is
some nice background kind of fueling the
attention that he is getting sort of
like
daniel johnston or wesley willis or r
stevie moore he sort of seems to be very
hands-on when it comes to promoting his
work and creating artwork for his music
as well and this really kind of hands-on
and grassroots approach that he's been
taking with with putting his music out
there has made him a bit of a folk hero
i guess but as i actually listened to
acoustimatic sorcery i just did not find
a lot i
enjoyed sadly i thought a lot of the
songs on here didn't really feature
lyrics i found interesting i thought a
lot of the structures of these songs and
the melodies got kind of monotonous i
didn't think the instrumentation was was
that great a lot of the time and
i didn't think these songs were were
that tuneful the instrumental foundation
of this lp is
guitar
vocals and a little bit of found
percussion and all of that
instrumentation is recorded onto
a tape recorder so you do kind of get
that taped sound and to me it sounds
like then it's taken off of the tape and
assembled or looped pretty quickly on a
computer on a lot of these tracks the
guitar whatever's being played doesn't
really sound like it's it's being
performed it's just kind of cycling in a
really
un interesting way underneath the vocals
which i would be okay with if i didn't
think the vocals were so kind of
hit or miss for example the track take
me away to me is actually a highlight on
here it's a really riveting track with
the vocal delivery beale brings on that
one it's really loud over modulated kind
of rough around the edges in a howl and
wolf kind of way and i really like
over-the-top delivery on the song
masquerade which is actually a bonus
track for this lp where he's talking
about going to this
masquerade party and just how
animated he is on that track just makes
it killer makes it entertaining but most
of the tracks on here like
cosmic queries or evenings kiss the
drama feels
kind of forced the sadness feels kind of
forced and
these tracks kind of expose this album's
biggest issue for me and that is
beal does not come off as being that
great of a storyteller some tracks on
here go down a road that is
beale throwing out a bunch of abstract
imagery that doesn't really connect in a
very obvious way but i'm sure it does
for him personally but the images aren't
really all that
out there
not to the point where it would be
thrilling to listen to them and they
don't come off as that as that vivid
either partially because of what he's
saying but partially because there's no
real
behind his singing and then there are
songs on here kind of like monotony
where the lyrics are very personal very
honest very focused on beal's feelings
but
they're really not that revealing when
somebody
wants to write a song about their
feelings you assume that they're just
going to kind of lay it out there on the
table they are going to expose some kind
of deep dark underbelly you're going to
get some kind of pure raw potent dose of
this person's
real feelings because a they have to
bottle these feelings up during the day
because nobody wants to hear about them
or b they have to bottle these feelings
up during the day because it would be
embarrassing to share them and not to
say that beal's feelings aren't
legitimate on the track monotony where
he kind of talks about being
generally bored and not really all that
sad not really all that happy kind of
blase i'm sure he actually feels that
way but the thing is the feelings he
talks about on this album are are kind
of ordinary so
it doesn't make them all that exciting
to listen to there are some spots on
here where i think beal does come
through as being really
entertaining like on ghost robot or
swing on low where the percussion is is
really kind of loud and quirky and just
over modulated and noisy and his vocals
are kind of doing a spoken word thing
with some lyrics that are very fun very
playful exposing the side of him that
just does not take itself that seriously
but those are pretty much the only spots
on here that i liked for the most part i
feel like this album just
drags it is just so
dry
it does not bring a lot of song
it does not bring a lot of lyrics or
personality because the influence is is
so obvious i feel like i have to go back
to a guy like daniel johnston and just
point out that that the songs
that that he put together especially the
stories especially the lyrics in his
tracks were so
dark we're just so depressing they were
so clever and witty and not that i wish
depression on on anybody or the kind of
of mental problems that daniel has has
fought with over the years i don't but
this is the kind of out of box thinking
that makes song writing entertaining for
listeners i just don't feel like
acoustomatic sorcery
has it
that's all
so i'm kind of feeling a strong three to
a light four
on this thing
